- prediction intent: predict dependent variable from type variables

- sub-intent: check if each variable combination matches predictor definitions
- sub-intent: apply prediction format ('generative function') to each variable combination
- sub-intent: store generative function for prediction intent
- prediction intent: check if generative function for variable combinations can generate the original function when combined with other generative functions
- containing intent: 'check that dependent variable is predicted with sub-intent prediction output (identified type variables)'

For example, to test if a set of generative type functions can produce the original output variable, you need a combine function to check for multiple methods of combining the generative functions that could generate the output variable (with some level of accuracy) - such as a 'averaging' combination function.

div.div:
Interface Query Assembly Visual
The intent organization process positions one input format (generative functions) as requiring another input format (type variables), so the type variable conversion is done first and hooked up to the generative function format as an input.
The intent organization process is the process of 'applying an interface' referenced elsewhere, finding the right abstract position of the components of the input, so that their connections & other components can be inferred with the application of consecutive structural layers.
This 'interface query design' process is an application of two problem-solving automation workflows from
https://github.com/outdreamer/build-a-cure/blob/master/docs/workflow/problem_solving_matching.md
:
1. Filter problem definition (Apply structure to Version 1 of query, which is the problem of "how to connect the objects in the input intent task") until it matches solution structure (an interface query that can complete the input intent task (tasks like 'find a relationship between variables' or 'check if these objects act similarly').
2. Apply structure (like using vectorization or systematization) to organize problem objects
Other problem-solving workflows can be used instead of this combination, such as by starting with a conceptual combination that the interface query needs to fulfill & applying structure, or starting from a query structure & removing attributes until it matches, etc.
